In-person instruction is currently being offered for students in grades K, 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 5th.  69 students are participating in a hybrid program. The families of 32 students chose not to participate in our on-campus program and decided to continue distance learning. We brought our kindergarten class back on November 9, 2020. Plans to bring in more classes were halted due to a surge in COVID-19 cases. In February, we started gradually on-boarding other classes in order to follow safety protocols. All classes are operating with a hybrid schedule in order to accommodate safety protocols and families who are choosing to continue distance learning for various reasons.

Our middle school students/teachers in grades 6th, 7th and 8th operate as a team. Although approval has been granted for 6th grade students to return to in-person learning, the return of 6th grade students without the return of 7th and 8th grade students would not fit with our program.

barrier_inperson:
Reason: Per Los Angles County Department of Public Health, Re-opening Protocols Appendix T1 (copy and pasted below):

"LEAs and schools are not required to provide specialized, in-person services, but those that do so may serve students with IEPs, students who are English Language learners, and students with needs that cannot be met through a virtual instruction platform. These students may be served as needed, provided that the overall number of students present on-site does not exceed 25% of total student body at any one time. Schools that have reopened for one or more of the grades served, but not for all grades served by the school, may also deliver these special services to a limited number of students in the grades not yet opened for full in person instruction. In that situation, the school may bring up to 25% of student enrollment in the grades not currently open on to campus at any one time for specialized support and services for high need students in those grades, as long as the school can adhere to distancing, infection control, and cohorting requirements."

barrier_inperson:
In three surveys this year, with the most recent in March 2021, the majority of our families in grades 7-12 prefer to remain distance through the end of the year.
In two faculty and staff surveys, the majority prefer to continue with distance learning through the end of the year.
We are a small school in one building, and our community has opted for a cautious approach for our older (grade 7-12) students.
We are reviewing plans to have grade 7-12 students opt to return to campus, but no date is set.

In addition, the majority of our classrooms do not have windows that open, and we are limited to MERV 11 filters for our HVAC.
Also, about 25% of our grade 7-12 student body is not in the Irvine area, or in the same time zone. They would not be able to come for in-person instruction. Offering in person instruction means that teachers would have students for each class in one of three situations: in person, online, or overseas.

barrier_notes: Most of our students live abroad, mainly Latin America or in other US States.
barrier_inperson: We are an online school only, we do not offer nor will face to face learning.
